{
  "masechta": "Zevachim",
  "daf": 49,
  "amud": "a",
  "macro_segments": [
    {
      "title": "Introduction to Eizehu Mekoman and the Question of Méakev by Ola",
      "display_title": "Eizehu Mekoman",
      "timestamp": "00:00",
      "micro_segments": [
        {
          "title": "Overview of the Mishna Eizehu Mekoman and its hermeneutic challenges",
          "display_title": "Mishna Overview",
          "timestamp": "00:00"
        },
        {
          "title": "The principle that something must be repeated by Kodshim to show it is méakev",
          "display_title": "Repetition & Méakev",
          "timestamp": "01:35"
        },
        {
          "title": "The question: Is North méakev by Ola if Chatat derives from Ola?",
          "display_title": "Chatat from Ola",
          "timestamp": "01:52"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "title": "The Temura Case: Derivative Kedusha Can Be Stronger Than Original",
      "display_title": "Temura Kedusha",
      "timestamp": "02:15",
      "micro_segments": [
        {
          "title": "Kodshim with a fixed mum cannot have Kedushat Haguf, only Kedushat Damim",
          "display_title": "Mum Kavua",
          "timestamp": "02:15"
        },
        {
          "title": "By Temura, even an animal with a mum can have Kedushat Haguf",
          "display_title": "Temura with Mum",
          "timestamp": "03:18"
        },
        {
          "title": "The Gemara explains: Temura's source is actual Kedusha, not created from nothing",
          "display_title": "Source of Kedusha",
          "timestamp": "04:09"
        },
        {
          "title": "Pesach that becomes Shelamim: Change of identity, not derivative strength",
          "display_title": "Pesach Identity",
          "timestamp": "06:21"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "title": "Deriving North as Méakev for Ola, Chatat, and Asham",
      "display_title": "North Méakev",
      "timestamp": "08:01",
      "micro_segments": [
        {
          "title": "The extra Hei in HaOla teaches that North is méakev for Ola",
          "display_title": "HaOla Extra Hei",
          "timestamp": "08:01"
        },
        {
          "title": "Asham is derived from Ola through the verse linking them",
          "display_title": "Asham Derivation",
          "timestamp": "08:43"
        },
        {
          "title": "All aspects of Asham (Shechita, blood, catcher) are in the North",
          "display_title": "Asham North",
          "timestamp": "09:02"
        },
        {
          "title": "The Asham Metzora verse repeats North to show it is méakev",
          "display_title": "Asham Metzora",
          "timestamp": "10:06"
        },
        {
          "title": "The principle of Davar Sheyaya Biklal Veyatza: exceptional cases cannot return to general rules without explicit statement",
          "display_title": "Davar Biklal",
          "timestamp": "11:43"
        },
        {
          "title": "By Asham Metzora, special blood-uses do not exempt from normal Chatat-like laws",
          "display_title": "Asham Special Uses",
          "timestamp": "12:50"
        },
        {
          "title": "Kachatas HaAsham Hu brings the exception back into the general category",
          "display_title": "Kachatas Lemachzir",
          "timestamp": "14:58"
        },
        {
          "title": "Debate: Can general rules be inferred from exceptions and vice versa?",
          "display_title": "Gamir Miklalo",
          "timestamp": "16:02"
        },
        {
          "title": "Resolution: The repetition of North teaches that it is méakev, not just a normal procedure",
          "display_title": "Repetition Teaches",
          "timestamp": "17:49"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "title": "The Principle of Davar Halamed Bihekesh: Linking to Both Ola and Chatat",
      "display_title": "Davar Halamed",
      "timestamp": "19:51",
      "micro_segments": [
        {
          "title": "Why does the verse link Asham to both Chatat and Ola?",
          "display_title": "Both Links",
          "timestamp": "19:51"
        },
        {
          "title": "If only Chatat were mentioned, Hekesh chain would work: Ola to Chatat to Asham",
          "display_title": "Chain Problem",
          "timestamp": "20:15"
        },
        {
          "title": "Ravina: By mentioning both, the verse teaches that transitive Hekesh is forbidden",
          "display_title": "Ravina's Answer",
          "timestamp": "20:47"
        },
        {
          "title": "The hermeneutic principle: Davar Halamed Behekesh Eino Chozer Umelamed Behekesh",
          "display_title": "Hekesh Principle",
          "timestamp": "21:17"
        },
        {
          "title": "By mentioning both Chatat and Ola, the verse teaches what is forbidden, proving the principle",
          "display_title": "Both Teaches Principle",
          "timestamp": "22:46"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "title": "Proof from Eimurim: Keasher Yuram Mishor Zevach Hashelamim",
      "display_title": "Eimurim Proof",
      "timestamp": "24:22",
      "micro_segments": [
        {
          "title": "How Eimurim are derived for Par He'elem Davar and Shirei Avoda Zara",
          "display_title": "Eimurim Sources",
          "timestamp": "24:22"
        },
        {
          "title": "Par Kohen Mashiach has Eimurim, but Par He'elem Davar does not explicitly mention them",
          "display_title": "Par Explicit",
          "timestamp": "25:06"
        },
        {
          "title": "Shirei Avoda Zara would require linking Kohen Mashiach to He'elem Davar to Avoda Zara",
          "display_title": "Shirei Chain",
          "timestamp": "26:54"
        },
        {
          "title": "The extra verse Keasher Yuram makes Eimurim seem explicitly stated by He'elem Davar",
          "display_title": "Keasher Yuram",
          "timestamp": "27:22"
        },
        {
          "title": "This extra verse proves that transitive Hekesh alone is insufficient",
          "display_title": "Extra Verse Proof",
          "timestamp": "28:31"
        },
        {
          "title": "Rav Papa challenges: Why not just state it explicitly by He'elem Davar?",
          "display_title": "Rav Papa",
          "timestamp": "28:50"
        },
        {
          "title": "The redundancy teaches the hermeneutic principle, just as Chatat and Ola do",
          "display_title": "Redundancy Teaches",
          "timestamp": "29:17"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "title": "Gemara Discusses Whether Hekesh Plus Gezeira Shava Is Permitted by Kodshim",
      "display_title": "Gezeira Shava",
      "timestamp": "31:02",
      "micro_segments": [
        {
          "title": "Proof from Tzaraat: Pricha on skin, garments, and hair are linked",
          "display_title": "Tzaraat Proof",
          "timestamp": "31:02"
        },
        {
          "title": "Skin to hair is a Hekesh; hair to garments is a Gezeira Shava",
          "display_title": "Two Methods",
          "timestamp": "32:42"
        },
        {
          "title": "Rabbi Yochanan: These limits apply only to Kodshim, not to other areas of Torah",
          "display_title": "Kodshim Only",
          "timestamp": "34:45"
        },
        {
          "title": "Can a law learned by Hekesh be applied further by Gezeira Shava in Kodshim?",
          "display_title": "Hekesh Plus Gezeira",
          "timestamp": "35:02"
        },
        {
          "title": "The Gemara proves from Kachatas HaAsham that Hekesh plus Gezeira Shava is also forbidden",
          "display_title": "Forbidden Combo",
          "timestamp": "35:39"
        },
        {
          "title": "If Hekesh plus Gezeira Shava worked, Kodesh Kodashim could link Chatat to Asham",
          "display_title": "If Allowed",
          "timestamp": "36:02"
        },
        {
          "title": "The fact that Ola is directly linked shows Hekesh plus Gezeira Shava is forbidden by Kodshim",
          "display_title": "Direct Link",
          "timestamp": "36:13"
        },
        {
          "title": "Suggestion: Maybe Chatat is too weak to support the link via Gezeira Shava alone",
          "display_title": "Chatat Weakness",
          "timestamp": "36:37"
        },
        {
          "title": "Kodesh Kodashim is stated so many times that Gezeira Shava would work regardless",
          "display_title": "Kodesh Extra",
          "timestamp": "36:37"
        }
      ]
    }
  ],
